DNS RECORD TYPES AND THEIR FUNCTIONS

DNS RECORDS ARE **ENTRIES STORED IN DNS SERVERS**. THEY TELL HOW DOMAIN NAMES SHOULD BE HANDLED — FOR EXAMPLE, WHERE TO SEND USERS WHEN THEY OPEN A WEBSITE OR SEND AN EMAIL.

EACH DNS RECORD HAS A **TYPE**, AND EACH TYPE HAS A **SPECIFIC PURPOSE**.

| RECORD TYPE | PURPOSE                                             | EXAMPLE                                        |
| ----------- | --------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| **A**       | MAPS DOMAIN → IPV4 ADDRESS                          | `YOUTUBE.COM → 142.250.196.110`                |
| **AAAA**    | MAPS DOMAIN → IPV6 ADDRESS                          | `EXAMPLE.COM → 2606:4700::6810:85E5`           |
| **CNAME**   | ALIAS (NICKNAME) FOR ANOTHER DOMAIN                 | `WWW.EXAMPLE.COM → EXAMPLE.COM`                |
| **MX**      | MAIL SERVER FOR DOMAIN                              | `EXAMPLE.COM MAIL HANDLED BY MAIL.EXAMPLE.COM` |
| **NS**      | NAMESERVERS FOR THE DOMAIN                          | `EXAMPLE.COM → NS1.EXAMPLE.COM`                |
| **TXT**     | STORES HUMAN-READABLE TEXT (OFTEN FOR VERIFICATION) | `SPF, DKIM, SITE-VERIFICATION`                 |
| **PTR**     | REVERSE DNS (IP → DOMAIN)                           | `8.8.8.8 → GOOGLE-PUBLIC-DNS-A.GOOGLE.COM`     |
| **SOA**     | START OF AUTHORITY, CONTAINS INFO ABOUT DOMAIN ZONE | HOLDS ADMIN EMAIL, REFRESH TIME, ETC.          |
| **SRV**     | DEFINES SERVICE AND PORT (USED BY VOIP, ETC.)       | `_SIP._TCP.EXAMPLE.COM → SERVER INFO`          |

---

[1] **A RECORD (ADDRESS RECORD)**

* MAPS A DOMAIN NAME TO AN **IPV4 ADDRESS**
* USED TO OPEN WEBSITES

EXAMPLE.COM → 93.184.216.34

[2] **AAAA RECORD**
* SAME AS A RECORD BUT FOR **IPV6 ADDRESS**
EXAMPLE.COM → 2606:4700::6810:85E5

[3] **CNAME RECORD (CANONICAL NAME)**
* ALIAS FOR ANOTHER DOMAIN
* USEFUL FOR `WWW.EXAMPLE.COM → EXAMPLE.COM`

[4] **MX RECORD (MAIL EXCHANGE)**
* TELLS WHICH MAIL SERVER HANDLES EMAILS
EXAMPLE.COM → MAIL.EXAMPLE.COM (PRIORITY 10)

[5] **NS RECORD (NAME SERVER)**
* TELLS WHICH DNS SERVERS HANDLE THE DOMAIN
EXAMPLE.COM → NS1.EXAMPLE.COM, NS2.EXAMPLE.COM

[6] **TXT RECORD**
* STORES ANY TEXT DATA
* COMMON USE: EMAIL VERIFICATION (SPF, DKIM), GOOGLE SITE VERIFICATION

[7] **PTR RECORD**
* USED FOR **REVERSE LOOKUP** (IP → DOMAIN)
8.8.8.8 → DNS.GOOGLE

[8] **SOA RECORD (START OF AUTHORITY)**

* HOLDS INFO ABOUT DOMAIN'S ZONE:

  * PRIMARY DNS SERVER
  * EMAIL OF ADMIN
  * SERIAL NUMBER, REFRESH TIME, ETC.

[9] **SRV RECORD**

* USED TO DEFINE SPECIFIC **SERVICES**, LIKE:
SIP._TCP.EXAMPLE.COM → TARGET SERVER WITH PORT INFO

| TYPE  | WHAT IT MAPS            | EXAMPLE                         |
| ----- | ----------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| A     | NAME → IPV4             | GOOGLE.COM → 142.250.196.110    |
| AAAA  | NAME → IPV6             | TEST.COM → 2606:4700::6810:85E5 |
| CNAME | ALIAS → ACTUAL NAME     | WWW → EXAMPLE.COM               |
| MX    | DOMAIN → MAIL SERVER    | EXAMPLE.COM → MAIL.EXAMPLE.COM  |
| NS    | DOMAIN → NAME SERVER    | EXAMPLE.COM → NS1.EXAMPLE.COM   |
| TXT   | DOMAIN → TEXT INFO      | SPF, DKIM, VERIFICATION         |
| PTR   | IP → NAME (REVERSE)     | 8.8.8.8 → DNS.GOOGLE            |
| SOA   | ZONE INFO               | ADMIN EMAIL, REFRESH SETTINGS   |
| SRV   | SERVICE → TARGET SERVER | VOIP, SIP, LDAP SERVICE SETUP   |
